For anyone looking to make a simple workaround for this issue Carl-P4's comment above is the key.

@Carl-P4's description of the problem (see below for quote) is still spot on and is a good base for working out your own solution. This is what works for me. Note: my solution does not require a separate screen and is updated to work with Dart v3.10.1/Flutter v3.38.3.

First, we need the FocusNote() declaration:
`final FocusNode _invisibleElevatedButtonNode = FocusNode();`

Make sure you dispose it properly:
```
@override
void dispose() {
    _invisibleElevatedButtonNode.dispose();
    super.dispose();
}
```
Somewhere in our widget tree we'll need an ElevatedButton to force-switch the focus to where it's needed . Not all existing ElevatedButton's will work and I haven't tested what exactly causes them to not work to circumvent this bug except for the example below:

```
ElevatedButton(
  onPressed: () {},
  focusNode: _invisibleElevatedButtonNode,
  style: ElevatedButton.styleFrom(
      //minimumSize: Size(1, 1), // DO NOT SET THIS OR THE BUG WILL STILL TRIGGER
      //maximumSize: Size(1, 1), // DO NOT SET THIS ALONE OR YOU'LL GET AN ERROR
      backgroundColor: Colors.transparent,
      foregroundColor: Colors.transparent,
      shadowColor: Colors.transparent,
      surfaceTintColor: Colors.transparent),
  child: SizedBox.shrink(),
),
```
Then, in key places we'll need to force the focus back to the "invisible" ElevatedButton. In one example from one app I have a dialog that opens with a TextField and a two actions: close & save. In the code for the dialog, I make sure that no matter how the dialog is closed the following code gets executed (`barrierDismissible` is not set) (if you don't already have it `import 'package:flutter/foundation.dart';
` is required for `kDebugMode` and `debugPrint`):
```
WidgetsBinding.instance.addPostFrameCallback((_) {
  if (mounted && _invisibleElevatedButtonNode.canRequestFocus) {
    _invisibleElevatedButtonNode.requestFocus();
  } else {
    if (kDebugMode) {
      debugPrint(
          'Changing focus failed:\nmounted: $mounted\ncanRequestFocus: ${_invisibleElevatedButtonNode.canRequestFocus}');
    }
  }
});
```

You can try to use your existing ElevatedButton's like I did at first but you'll notice the same thing I did too - some of them won't work to circumvent the bug. I suspect it has to do with certain options that prevent the circumvention from working (like how setting `minimumSize` prevents the circumvention from working in the above example).

Carl-P4:
> Resolved my issue.
> 
> If the user types in the text fields that trigger the keyboard and uses the keyboard enter key to change the focus then the keyboard would retract when the focus ends on an ElevatedButton.
> 
> But if they closed the keyboard with the keyboard close button or navigate to the next screen with the keyboard shown, tapping anywhere on the next screen, which uses containers, text and images only, triggers the keyboard repeatedly. Closing the keyboard hides it until the next tap.
> 
> Pressing Tab on the touch keyboard then makes it retract and not pop up again.
> 
> To solve this I placed a transparent ElevatedButton on the second screen and forced it's focus. Then it doesn't matter what the user does to the keyboard before navigating to the second screen. The focus on the ElevatedButton on the second screen retracts the keyboard.

We can't thank you enough @Carl-P4 for your post because it not only describes the issue perfectly but it also allows us to create simple workarounds that will not require any changes if the "bug" is ever fixed.

Note that the following will not work to circumvent this problem (no idea why, haven't looked into it other than to confirm it doesn't circumvent the problem):
`FocusManager.instance.primaryFocus?.unfocus();`

@Jon-Salmon reports that `.nextFocus` will work but I haven't tested it because sending the focus to random places (the build order isn't always the same) is not ideal for me. But, it's here in case it will work for you:
> Having had a play, I've found that calling `FocusManager.instance.primaryFocus?.unfocus();` results in this error where as `FocusManager.instance.primaryFocus?.nextFocus();` seems to work as expected. I'm not sure what this tells us about where the error is.

Note: If you have no need for the OSK Windows IME can be completely disabled (for the running app only) in `win32_window.cpp` and this problem will never occur in the first place:
```
#include <imm.h>
#pragma comment(lib, "imm32.lib")
```
and then just before `HWND window = CreateWindow(` put this:
`ImmDisableIME((DWORD)-1);`

If you still have need for an automatic OSK after disabling the Windows one, the package [flutter_onscreen_keyboard ](https://pub.dev/packages/flutter_onscreen_keyboard) works well. However, it does not have it's own built in physical keyboard detection so if you need that you will have to add that yourself. If there's never a physical keyboard attached this could be an ideal solution for you if you want a predictable, customizable OSK.

Interesting side notes during debugging and testing to create workarounds for this issue:
- Manually pressing the ElevatedButton (that is used to change focus to in the workaround using `.requestFocus`) does not prevent the bug from happening (tested on a sign in screen with two TextField's and an ElevatedButton for sign in. All I had to do was `requestFocus` to the ElevatedButton that was just pressed in the onPressed event for the ElevatedButton and it prevents the bug from occurring).
- At one point I attempted to send the focus back to a ListTile and doing so does not prevent the bug from triggering. That's when I implemented the "invisible" ElevatedButton example above and discovered that setting `minimumSize` prevents the workaround from working.
- Not all ElevatedButton's will work for the workaround. As noted above setting `minimumSize: Size(1, 1)` prevents the workaround from working. There may be other options that also prevent the workaround from working but I haven't tested them because I just need a solution that works.

